   issn = {10959572},
   issue = {August},
   journal = {NeuroImage},
   keywords = {Attention networks,Auditory attention,Connectomics,Human Connectome Project,Resting state functional connectivity,Visual attention},
   note = {Previous work showed an interleaved pattern of visual and auditory biased regions along the precentral sulcus (lPFC). Visual areas connected to IPS/TOS, and auditory to STG.<br/><br/>Reproducing based on the connectivity among task-based ROIs from a small independent sample (which replicated the layouts) in each individual from the 500 HCP resting dataset.<br/><br/>rsFC confirmed selective connectivity between frontal and posterior visual areas, and frontal and temporal autitory areas per individual. Connectivity strength within these sensory networks was greater in the right hemi for vision, and left hemi for auditory. Builds into indiv rsFC topic.<br/><br/>Segmenting the interleaved ROIs into strips showed that the connectivity with posterior sensory areas was refined, sinusoidal along the dorsal-ventral axis, and was not different at the roi borders. Very gradient like.<br/><br/>Whole brain difference between IPS and STG FC confirmed this and revealed additional, more anterior areas of visual and auditory bias in lPFC.<br/><br/><b>Connection: this takes a closer look at the ability to reproduce task-evoked mapping using resting state (specifically like Cole et al 2014), and is an example of the double-dissociation suggested by Passingham, Stephens and Kotter (2002). Also, visual biased areas include FEF, so the IPS -&gt; FEF pattern matches Yeo et al (2011). An auditory biased region resembles novel 55b from Glasser et al 2016, although disimilarities here suggest a subdivision of it.</b>},
   pages = {362-372},
   pmid = {28830764},
