   note = {Mainly concerned with producing a general and psychologically flexible theory of consumer choice based on cog psych and microecon. People derive value not only from items, but also from a transaction.<br/><br/>Three building components: <br/><br/>1. How values under prospect theory are compounded (jointly or separately depending on the combo of gains and losses). Maximizing subjective value is done by segregating gains (v(x) + v(y)) and integrating losses (v(-x-y)). Gains or losses governed by reference point.<br/><br/>2. How transaction utilities are produced by these combinations. Transaction utility, which differs from acquisition utility and based on reference price, fairness, and personal value of prospect. <br/><br/>3. How such utilities operate within budgetary constraints. Once a transaction value is computed, you can make a decision by seeing how much more valuable it is than it's cost, compared to a budget k. This budget is time and category specific, so it can't just be total wealth. This goes against traditional econ concept of fungibility (money has no labels)<br/><br/>A cool note is that the survey examples he uses follow the nonlinearities of subjective value without the need of gambles (like K&amp;T)},
