   note = {Examining rsFC in terms of reliability/data-requirements, precise topography, and task-correspondence in 10 overly-sampled individuals (MSC)<br/><br/>Networks were robust to density variations and not tied to curvature. Even though all individuals showed idiosyncratic rsFC layouts of canonical networks, some unique areas became visible that were otherwise obsucred by averaging (e.g. mPFC gap with differential connectivity)<br/><br/>within subject reliabilities for many network metrics asymptote at around 20 minutes, and modularity even less. But they call for longer based on average across subjects. Less than that can introduce bias into estimates.<br/><br/>&quot;Responses are robust but poorly localized when all [motor] data from all subjects are tested (MSCavg). Average responses are sparse when data quantity is matched to the individual contrasts (Data-matched avg).&quot;<br/><br/>In all but 2 participants there was a common circular pattern of preferential connectivity among the big networks (spring network graph) that was lost when averaged (averaged net layout similar to Power et al 2011)<br/><br/>Individualized task activity for motor topography and scene detection was better matched to rsFC within than across individuals--or avg (like Tarvo et al 2016)},
