@article{Braga2018,
   abstract = {Examination of large-scale distributed networks within the individual reveals details of cortical network organization that are absent in group-averaged studies. One recent discovery is that a distributed transmodal network, often referred to as the 'de-fault network', is comprised of two separate but closely interdigitated networks, only one of which is coupled to posterior parahippocampal cortex. Not all studies of individuals have identified clear separation of the same networks. Here, functional MRI (fMRI) participants (n=2; human; females) scanned intensively across 31 sessions again revealed the two intertwined networks. The networks were observed across analytical (seed-based connectivity and parcellation) and data projection (volume and surface) methods. To gain further insight into the anatomical details, additional participants (n=3; human; females) were examined with high-resolution (1.35mm) fMRI at 7T. The two networks were identified with separate regions localized to adjacent portions of the cortical ribbon, sometimes with their close juxtaposition evident inside the same sulcus. Anterior and posterior midline regions previously implicated as core hubs of the default network revealed near complete spatial separation of the two networks. The network coupled to parahippocampal cortex also revealed a separate region directly within the hippocampus at or near the subiculum. These collective results support that the well-studied default network is composed of at least two distinct spatially juxtaposed networks. Fine spatial details and juxtapositions of the two networks can be identified within individuals at high resolution, providing insight into the network organization of association cortex and placing further constraints on interpretation of group-averaged neuroimaging data. The association cortex is comprised of distributed networks that are spatially organized as a set of parallel networks involving temporal, parietal, frontal, and anterior and posterior mid-line regions (},
