   journal = {NeuroImage},
   keywords = {Functional connectivity,Inter-subject registration,Surface-based methods},
   note = {Validation of an algorithm (FCA) that uses similarity of connectivity vectors (i.e. fingerprints) across individuals to align functional areas.<br/><br/>The brain was divided into two large functional clusters: extrinsic (posterior) and intrinsic (anterior, more DN-FP-like).<br/><br/>Compared to anatomical alignment, time-series-based and FCA functional alignment:<br/>- Produced similarly better inter-subject correlations of node activity (fig 4).<br/>- Produced higher similarities in connectivity vectors across subjects, but FCA performed better in whole brain, extrinsic, and intrinsic partitions (fig 7).<br/>- Show benefits of functional alignment in classification accuracies for various stimuli across subjects, but still not as good as classifications within-subjects.<br/>- Different sets of stimulus sequences produced very similar FC warpings of the data overall, “whereas FTSA is effective only for aligning responses to identical stimulus sequences”<br/><br/><br/>Connection: Algorithm similar to the Yeo et al 2011 vector-based clustering, but in individuals. Fingerprint-based alignment matches PPA better than time-series based alignment (connect to Kanwisher 2010)},
