jected to area 23. Finally, a rostromedial part of visual association area 19 also projected to area 23. The origin and termination of these connections were expressed in a number of different laminar patterns. Most corticocortical connections arose in layer I11 and to a lesser extent layer V, while others, eg., those from the cortex of the superior temporal sulcus, had a n equal density of cells in both layers I11 and V. In one instance projections to area 24 arose almost entirely from layer V of areas TH, TL, and TF. Furthermore, although most projections terminated in layers 1-111 of cingulate cortex, those of the amygdala to rostral area 24 terminated in deep layer I and layer I1 while area Opt projections to area 23 terminated mainly in layers I, 11, and IV. Four classes of cortical connections have been characterized and each may play a role in the sensorimotor functions of cingulate cortex. These},
